Observations from different classes show unique patterns on 3D plots. It is quite easy to distinguish one class from another examining their plots.

Observations from different classes show relatively unique patterns on when plotted on 2D, but the patterns are not as distinguishing as they were in 3D plots. There is an observable reduction in separability of classes due to reduction in dimensions. 2D plots would still help but they are definitely not as reliable as 3D plots since observations from different classes might show similar patterns on 2D.

The first component has the highest proportion of variance whether PCA is applied on whole data or on each class separately. The patterns on new plots are similar to those on previous plots with little changes. Changes might be due to our observing the patterns at specific instances.

xtrain <- mutate(xtrain, V1 = xtrain_v1_temp)
ytrain_edit <- ytrain[, -1]
ztrain_edit <- ztrain[, -1]
whole_data <- cbind(xtrain, ytrain_edit, ztrain_edit)
whole_data_edit <- whole_data[, -1]
whole_data_edit <- scale(whole_data_edit)
distance <- dist(whole_data_edit, method = "euclidean")
dist_matrix <- as.matrix(distance)
dist_md <- cmdscale(dist_matrix, k = 2)
data_md <- select(whole_data, V1)
data_md <- mutate(data_md, axis_one = dist_md[, 1], axis_two = dist_md[, 2], class = as.factor(V1))
ggplot(data_md) + geom_point(aes(x = axis_one, y = axis_two, colour = class)) + xlab("Axis 1") + ylab("Axis 2") + ggtitle("Multidimensional Scale")

Points from the class seem to be grouped, but the picture is not very clear. The plot might help showing that there is a noticeable difference between the distribution of points from different classes, but one definitely cannot distinguish one class from another depending solely on this plot.
